      "title": "Pivotal role of dermal IL-17-producing оБІоБ§ T cells in skin inflammation",
      "abstract": "Summary Interleukin-23 (IL-23) and CD4 + T helper 17 (Th17) cells are thought to be critical in psoriasis pathogenesis. Here, we report that IL-23 predominantly stimulated dermal ќ≥ќі T cells to produce IL-17 that led to disease progression. Dermal ќ≥ќі T cells constitutively expressed the IL-23 receptor (IL-23R) and transcriptional factor RORќ≥t. IL-17 production from dermal ќ≥ќі T cells was independent of ќ±ќ≤ T cells. The epidermal hyperplasia and inflammation induced by IL-23 were significantly decreased in T cell receptor ќі-deficient ( Tcrd вИТ/вИТ ) and IL-17 receptor-deficient ( Il17ra вИТ/вИТ ) mice but occurred normally in Tcra вИТ/вИТ mice. Imiquimod-induced skin pathology was also significantly decreased in Tcrd вИТ/вИТ mice. Perhaps further promoting disease progression, IL-23 stimulated dermal ќ≥ќі T cell expansion. In psoriasis patients, ќ≥ќі T cells were greatly increased in affected skin and produced large amounts of IL-17. Thus, IL-23-responsive dermal ќ≥ќі T cells are the major IL-17 producers in the skin and may represent a novel target for the treatment of psoriasis."
    }
